abstract: If Ms. Nixon becomes the state’s first female governor, her wife, Christine Marinoni, would become the state’s first gay first lady.
snippet: If Ms. Nixon becomes the state’s first female governor, her wife, Christine Marinoni, would become the state’s first gay first lady.
lead_paragraph: The tabloid media had camped outside the five-story prewar building on Manhattan’s Upper West Side, hoping to catch a glimpse of the mystery woman who had stolen the heart of Cynthia Nixon, the “Sex and the City” star.

headline_main: Beside Cynthia Nixon, a Potential First Lady to Blaze a Trail of Her Own
headline_print_headline: Alongside Nixon, a Potential First Lady May Blaze Her Own Trail

abstract: The pairing of Cynthia Nixon and Jumaane Williams in New York, opposing Gov. Andrew Cuomo and Lt. Gov. Kathy Hochul, may not be as odd as it seems.
snippet: The pairing of Cynthia Nixon and Jumaane Williams in New York, opposing Gov. Andrew Cuomo and Lt. Gov. Kathy Hochul, may not be as odd as it seems.
lead_paragraph: During a recent canvass in Brooklyn, volunteers on Cynthia Nixon’s campaign for governor encountered an unexpected situation: Some voters were far less familiar with Ms. Nixon than with her running mate, Jumaane D. Williams.

headline_main: The Lives They Loved: Charles Bradley

abstract: Republicans and Democrats sparred over censorship on social media, as the Justice Department said it would examine whether the services were purposely “stifling the free exchange of ideas.”
snippet: Republicans and Democrats sparred over censorship on social media, as the Justice Department said it would examine whether the services were purposely “stifling the free exchange of ideas.”
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Republicans accused Twitter of being biased against conservatives on Wednesday, drawing rebukes from Democrats in a congressional hearing that illustrated how partisan lines are increasingly being drawn on social media.

abstract: His sprawling menu was legendary, and so was his penchant for tossing out potential customers who didn’t get the concept of his neighborhood eatery.
snippet: His sprawling menu was legendary, and so was his penchant for tossing out potential customers who didn’t get the concept of his neighborhood eatery.
lead_paragraph: Kenny Shopsin, the colorful proprietor of a fabled Manhattan restaurant where the menu is vast and the customer has never been king, died on Sunday at his home in the West Village. He was 76.

headline_main: Kenny Shopsin, Brash Owner of a Quirky Restaurant, Dies at 76
headline_print_headline: Kenny Shopsin, Restaurateur Who Couldn’t Stomach Patrons, Dies at 76

abstract: For Ms. McCray, the wife of Mayor Bill de Blasio, this is her first solo endorsement; the mayor has not endorsed any candidates in statewide races.
snippet: For Ms. McCray, the wife of Mayor Bill de Blasio, this is her first solo endorsement; the mayor has not endorsed any candidates in statewide races.
lead_paragraph: As Chirlane McCray has quietly moved toward a more prominent political profile alongside her husband, Mayor Bill de Blasio, she has decided to make her first solo endorsement as first lady — backing Zephyr Teachout for state attorney general.

headline_print_headline: McCray Endorses Teachout In Race for Attorney General

abstract: The annual J’Ouvert celebration has struggled with violence and the effects of increased security on its freewheeling nature. But the jab jab dancers remain its energetic core.
snippet: The annual J’Ouvert celebration has struggled with violence and the effects of increased security on its freewheeling nature. But the jab jab dancers remain its energetic core.
lead_paragraph: J’Ouvert, the uninhibited early-hours parade and street party that occurs each Labor Day, has long been a celebration of freedom. And one of the purest expressions of that freedom is called jab jab — a drum-fueled frenzy in which masqueraders paint themselves black with old motor oil, put horns on their heads and dance for hours through the streets of Brooklyn.

abstract: The manager crouched behind the plate to illustrate his argument in a confrontation with an umpire. Then the Yankees’ offense came to life.
snippet: The manager crouched behind the plate to illustrate his argument in a confrontation with an umpire. Then the Yankees’ offense came to life.
lead_paragraph: Under normal circumstances, Yankees Manager Aaron Boone is a pretty even-keeled fellow. He greets the news media before his daily pregame sessions with a jaunty “Good day” and peppers his speech with the lingo of a Southern California surfer dude. Many times, he can barely stifle a smile when asked a question that his predecessor, Joe Girardi, might have considered provocative.
